'''Singanallur Venkataramana Iyer Sahasranamam'''<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Oxford companion to Indian theatre|last=Lal|first=Ananda|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=2004|page=403 |author-link=Ananda Lal}}</ref> (29 November 1913&nbsp;– 19 February 1988), also known as '''S. V. S.''',<ref name="SVS" /> was an Indian actor and director. Primarily a theatre actor, he also worked in over 200 films, mainly in [[Tamil cinema]].

== Early life ==
Sahasranamam was born on 29 November 1913 at [[Singanallur]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?redir_esc=y&id=JrgZAAAAYAAJ&dq=S.+V.+Sahasranamam+1913&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Sahasranamam|title=Reference India|date=1975|publisher=Tradesman & Men India|volume=1|page=94}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kalyanamalaimagazine.com/Content/Thiraichuvai/Mar13_1_15/Potpourri_of_titbits_about_Tamil_cinema_SV_Sahasranamam.html |title=Serial story, Thiraichuvai&nbsp;– Potpourri of titbits about Tamil cinema, S.V.Sahasranamam |last=Majordasan |website=Kalyanamalai Magazine |at=page 1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130831222134/http://www.kalyanamalaimagazine.com/Content/Thiraichuvai/Mar13_1_15/Potpourri_of_titbits_about_Tamil_cinema_SV_Sahasranamam.html |archive-date=31 August 2013 |dead-url=no |access-date=29 April 2014}}</ref> He was the fourth child born to Venkatraman and Parvathi.<ref name="SVS">{{Cite news|url=http://tamil.thehindu.com/cinema/cinema-others/%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%B5%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B4%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%8B%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B4%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A8%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4-%E0%AE%AA%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B1%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D/article9382419.ece|title=நினைவும் விருதும்: வாழும்போதும் வாழ்ந்த பிறகும்...|date=25 November 2016|work=[[The Hindu (Tamil)|The Hindu Tamil]] |access-date=11 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021073451/https://tamil.thehindu.com/cinema/cinema-others/%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%B5%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B4%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%8B%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B4%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A8%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4-%E0%AE%AA%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B1%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%81%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D/article9382419.ece# |archive-date=21 October 2018 |dead-url=no}}</ref> Because of his interest in acting, he left his home at an early age to join the Madurai Sri Balashanmuganandha Sabha, a popular theatre group, which was later renamed T. K. S. Nataka Sabha.<ref name="newindianexpress1">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/article1361783.ece|title=Theatre artiste's birth centenary celebrations held|date=1 December 2012|work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=29 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429204036/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/article1361783.ece |archive-date=29 April 2014 |dead-url=no}}</ref>

== Career ==
Several years after he joined T. K. S. Nataka Sabha, Sahasranamam started his own theatre group titled "Seva Stage". With that, he staged several popular plays such as ''Kangal'', ''Irulum Oliyum'' and ''Vadivelu Vaathiyar''. These plays were later adapted into feature films and were commercially successful. He also adapted the novels of writers such as [[B. S. Ramiah]], T. Janakiraman and Ku Pa Rajagopalan, and made them into feature films.<ref name="newindianexpress1" /> Although Sahasranamam was also successful in cinema, having acted in over 200 films since debuting in that field with ''[[Menaka (1935 film)|Menaka]]'' (1935),<ref name="theekkathir" /> he always considered theatre his main interest.<ref name="kalyanamalaimagazine1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kalyanamalaimagazine.com/Content/Thiraichuvai/Mar13_1_15/Potpourri_of_titbits_about_Tamil_cinema_SV_Sahasranamam_page1.html|title=Serial story, Thiraichuvai&nbsp;– Potpourri of titbits about Tamil cinema, S.V.Sahasranamam|last=Majordasan|website=Kalyanamalai Magazine|at=page 2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107092351/http://www.kalyanamalaimagazine.com/Content/Thiraichuvai/Mar13_1_15/Potpourri_of_titbits_about_Tamil_cinema_SV_Sahasranamam_page1.html |archive-date=7 January 2015 |dead-url=no |access-date=29 April 2014}}</ref>

== Awards ==
Sahasranamam won the [[Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]] for Acting (Tamil) in 1967,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401211355/http://sangeetnatak.gov.in:80/sna/awardeeslist.htm |title=Sangeet Natak Akademi Puraskar (Akademi Awards) |website=[[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] |access-date=21 November 2018}}</ref> and received the [[Sangeetha Kalasikhamani]] award in 1980 by the Indian Fine Arts Society, Chennai.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theindianfineartssociety.com/oldevents.html |title=Awardees of Sangeetha Kalasikhamani |website=The Indian Fine Art Society |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926175847/http://www.theindianfineartssociety.com/oldevents.html# |archive-date=26 September 2018 |dead-url=no |access-date=21 November 2018}}</ref>

== Illness and death ==
Between March 1974 and February 1988, Sahasranamam had suffered more than five heart attacks. He had chosen the artists for the play ''Nandha Vilakku'', authored by novelist/dramatist Krishnamani, and asked them to come for a rehearsal on 21 February. But he suffered a heart attack on 19 February 1988 and died at 4:30&nbsp;pm [[Indian Standard Time|IST]].<ref name="kalyanamalaimagazine1" /><ref name="theekkathir">{{Cite news|url=https://theekkathir.in/2013/12/02/%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%B8%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%B8%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%AE%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%A8%E0%AF%82%E0%AE%B1%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B1%E0%AE%BE/|title=எஸ். வி. சகஸ்ரநாமம் நூற்றாண்டு|last=|first=|date=2 December 2013|work=[[Theekkathir]]|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211103844/https://theekkathir.in/2013/12/02/%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%B8%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%B8%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%A8%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%AE%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%A8%E0%AF%82%E0%AE%B1%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%B1%E0%AE%BE/|archive-date=11 December 2018|dead-url=no|language=ta}}</ref> Sahasranamam's son S. V. S. Khumar is also an actor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/stage-service-and-sahasranamam/article5425349.ece|title=Stage, Service and Sahasranamam|last=Rangarajan|first=Malathi|date=5 December 2013|work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=3 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222220317/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/stage-service-and-sahasranamam/article5425349.ece |archive-date=22 December 2017 |dead-url=no}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newstodaynet.com/index.php/2017/12/06/dramatist-svs-104-birth-anniversary-remembered/|title=Chennai dramatist S V Sahasranamam remembered|last=Srinivasan|first=G.|date=6 December 2017|work=[[The News Today (India)|The News Today]] |access-date=27 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222111026/https://www.newstodaynet.com/index.php/2017/12/06/dramatist-svs-104-birth-anniversary-remembered/ |archive-date=22 December 2017 |dead-url=yes}}</ref>

